hey folks just wanted to bring to everyone is attention the fact that it is a reasonably good time to do some meteor observing at the moment it is pretty much new moon yay
dark skies
 and being the southern hemisphere winter we get some long dark nights so that is all cool anyway
at the moment we have got three halfdecent meteor showers active
one the delta aquariids is one of the better showers of the year for southern hemisphere observers though not a match for mays eta aquariids or decembers geminids
at its peak this coming weekend it has a forecast zhr of 25 for those who are not familiar with it the zhr of a meteor shower is the zenithal hourly rate it is an estimate of the number of meteors you would see in an hour under absolutely perfect conditions
so in reality you will see fewer meteors than the zhr
meteors in a given meteor shower appear to radiate from a certain point in the night sky the radiant of the shower
the higher the radiant is in the sky the more meteors you will see from that shower
if the radiant is below the horizon you will not see anything from the shower as the meteors will all be hitting the far side of the earth
so for the delta aquariids the radiant is near the star delta aquarii
when that star is low in the sky the rates you see from the shower will be lower and the higher the star gets the better the rates you see will be
on saturday night skat delta aquarii will culminate be at its highest at around 215am which means that is when you can expect to see peak rates from the meteor shower
make sense
the delta aquariids are the main event
skat rises in the relatively early evening at the moment meaning that shower meteors are visible all night but decent rates will only be seen once it has climbed a bit in the sky
if you want to check when it rises where you are go to stellarium the web version is great but i do not know if i can link it here
 search for skat and then lock it in and move time forwards and backwards
ampx200b on top of the delta aquariids there are two other more minor showers that peak around the same time
the alpha capricornids are great although they are a weak shower zhr around 5 at peak they have a reputation for producing lots of bright meteors and even fireballs
where delta aquariid meteors are mediumfast the alpha capricornids are markedly slower which makes them a good target for astrophotographers though the low rates can be frustrating
then we have the piscis austrinids another minor shower with peak zhrs of around 5 meteors from this shower are faster than alpha capricornids but slower than delta aquariids ampx200b the radiants of the three showers are relatively close to each other in the sky meaning that all are high in the sky for those of us in the southern hemisphere for the hours around midnight and into the early morning
ampx200b what does all this mean
well this weekend is a good time to get out somewhere dark rug up nice and warm and lay out under the stars for a few hours take a friend and a warm drink and lie back and relax i am not promising a meteor storm or anything like that but the rates can be quite impressive when added together
a couple of years back at an astro meet up here in queensland i counted 50 meteors in three hours from the three showers combined so a pretty nice treat in the middle of winter ampx200b as for where to look a good tip to maximise the number of meteors you see is to work out where the radiants of the showers are and to look about 45 degrees above the horizon about thirty to 45 degrees left or right of that point wherever the sky is darkest
that is a good way of maximising the number of meteors you will see by maximising the amount of the earths atmosphere you are looking for without looking so low in the sky that you are looking through loads of gunk and grot in the sky
ampx200b this meteor shower calendar on spaceaustralias website has some good finder chats if you are interested in going out looking it is obviously got an australiacentric theme but the charts should help wherever you are enjoy
