so anyway we know of only two main states a planetary object can be in while in orbit tidally locked like the moon is to earth and not tidally locked like the planets are to the sun
but is it possible for a planetary body to be psudo tidally locked
basically its a state in between these two extremes where say a moon for example has a odd orbit around its planet that while at times make it locked into one spot for some time but due to the influence of another moon nearby gets nudged so that the moon begins to get tidally unlocked at least for a short period
like perhaps its due to another moon of simular size and gravity and its gravitational influcence rubs off on its neighbor
i know we have yet to encounter such a odd phenominon but is such a thing even remotely possible
note this is just specculation on my part but would love to hear your thoughts i will aslo ask this on other subreddits if you feel this is inapproprite
there are 4 known categories of black holes in the universe miniature stellar mass intermediate and supermassive
for this discussion let us pick out stellar mass black holes and supermassive black holes
as we know slipping past the event horizon of a black hole means an object light too is at a point of no return and subject to the tidal effect caused by a black holes immense gravitational force the said object will be spaghettified
that being said i always felt that it is the smaller black holes that are far more dangerous
their event horizons are smaller and by virtue of their size they are also immensely dense simple math
with supermassive black holes the event horizons are massive and thus it is also more likely that one could stay there for longer than they could on the event horizons of much smaller black holes
however i recently read an article that explains very precisely why this is the case
it is due to the tidal force exerted by a given black hole
the difference in the force exerted on ones head and the force exerted on ones feet will be much larger in smaller black holes than they are in larger ones
and as i mentioned already that spaghettification depends on the tidal effect you will get much more spaghettified by a smaller black hole
