clear skies
in science communication when mentioning an astronomical distance it is very common to put a distance in light years into the time when the light was emitted for this object which is 70 million light years away the light was emitted when the dinosaurs still roamed the earth or something similar
i think that this makes very little sense and is at best irrelevant
there are four reasons for this
1 the average person has about as much idea about how long ago things are compared with how far things are
people know dinosaurs existed very long ago but exactly how long
the average joe on the street does not have a concrete idea
so linking distances to times does not make too much sense
2 it encourages confusion
there are countless times i had to explain that even though the light was emitted 70 million years ago the dinosaurs would not have seen what we are seeing because of causality
3 the light travel times of local universe objects i am calling local universe anything below z01 is quite irrelevant because the universe did not change that much in the meantime
the universe we are detecting might as well be now
it is more meaningful to describe sn1987a as happening 35 years ago rather than thousands of years ago
for high redshift objects surethe properties of these objects are different that the look back time is relevant but not local galaxies
4 it does not actually explain anything usually
since distance units in science communication is usually light years you are essentially replacing the unit in distance with the unit in time with the same value
this does not actually reduce the issue of big numbers to the layman but actually just kicks the can down the road
if people know what lightyear means then adding the sentence about the light travel time does not add anything to the discussion
i look forward to hearing your opinions on this
would it just be an exo moon 
or would it become an asteroid 
